Monthly labour market stats update

Using styles derived from Edward Tufte

Paul Bivand

2016-03-28

Introduction

This is a bit of a test of using the JSON downloads from ONS as well as the Tufte styles.

Notes:

  1. The ONS JSON downloads are rounded to the published figures. This means that any calculated figures may not be the same as published ONS changes, which are based on unrounded figures then rounded after calculation. The ONS Excel downloads are unrounded (and also in absolute numbers not thousands);
  2. My default image is to show time trends over the last two years, with y axis limits defaulting to a margin around the maximum and minimum occurring within that timeframe. The reason for this is that Im interested in trying to find out whether there is any recent change in trend. If the minimum was set to zero then these changes would not be visible.

Lets download the figures from ONS for unemployment and the unemployment rate, and then create ggplot2 sparklines and a dygraphs interactive with a default 2-year range set. The dygraphs can display the whole range, but on opening should show just the last 2 years.

That downloaded all the data with a 1971 base year. The first data is for January to March 1971, and is shown as February here. Data before March-May 1992 is modelled from annual Labour Force Surveys and prior datasets such as the Claimant Count and Employee Jobs estimates. The pre-1992 estimates are niticeably smoother than the post-1992 figures that are based on the continuously running Labour Force Survey.

For the sparklines in ggplot2 I need to select the relevant series and transform them into a data.frame.

Unemployment (ILO definition) and the Unemployment rate

First thoughts: The sparklines are OK but the series titles run off the chart and the date numbering is funky. The unemployment numbers are thousands which can be multiplied by 1000 to give actuals, but getting big.marks as commas might be hard.
